{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601706/1938022701/0747.xml":{"full_text":"FINANCIAL AND MARKET\n1 L TREND OF WEEK\nPART FOUR\u2014FINANCIAL AND CLASSIFIED\ngfye jfamflan fjfaf\nt\nCLASSIFIED ADVERTISING\nPAGES THREE TO THIRTEEN\nFOURTEEN PAGES.\nWASHINGTON, D. C., FEBRUARY 27, 1938.\nWASHINGTON GAS\nEARNINGS SHOW\nSUBSTANTIAE GAIN\nJanuary Profit at $168,202,\nAgainst $126,040 for\nSame 1937 Month.\nRETAIL SALESDECLINE\nMODERATELY IN WEEK\nDecrease of 8.94 Per Cent Leaves\nStore Volume 4.86 Per Cent\nUnder 1937 Period.\nBy EDWARD C. STONE.\nScoring a substantial gam in earn\nings in January, the Washington Gas\nLight Co. reported to the Public Utili\nties Commission yesterday that net\nincome totaled $168,202. compared\nwith $126,040 in January last year,\nan increase of $42,160. 4\nThe monthly report filed with the\ncommission showed operating reve\nnues of $847,661, a sharp increase of\n$117,736 over the figure of $729,925\na year ago. Operating expenses were\nkept well in hand, but Increased by\n$77,588 from $517,482 in January,\n1937, to $595,070 this year.\nDeduction of expenses left net op\nerating revenues of $252,591, or an\nincrease of $40,148 over January, 1937.\nAfter all deductions for interest and\namortization, the notable net gain\nof more than $42,000 was established.\nThe company also reported gas sales\nof 1.249.232 cubic feet, representing an\nincrease of 18.9 per cent, compared\nwith the same month last year. As of\nJanuary 31. 1938, there were 149.722\nmeters in service, compared with 144.\n902 on the same date last year,\ngain of 48,020.\nD. C. Trade Slightly Lower.\nLargely attributed to the compara\ntive lateness of Easter this year, de\npartment store sales in Washington\nduring the last week were 4.88 per\ncent under the same week a year ago\nand 8.94 per cent below the previous\nweek, the Commerce Department re\nported yesterday.\nBank clearings in the Capital to\ntaled $17,488,429. against $19,298,518\na year ago, the review added, while\nbuilding permits were valued at $358,\n400. which included $230,000 for a\nnew theater, in comparison with\n$587,500 a year ago. The number of\ntourists in the city was much larger\nthan in the previous week, but not\nas large as a year ago.\nRetail trade in the rest of the fifth\ndistrict was influenced by generally\nunfavorable weather, registering slight\ndeclines from the previous week and\nthe like period in 1937. Special pro\nmotional efforts in Baltimore met with\ngood consumer response, the* Com\nmerce report said, where buying from\nwholesale firms is still cautious. In\nstallment sales were up 8 per cent In\nCharleston, S. C.\nIn its latest national business sum\nmary the Federal Reserve Board yes\nterday reported a definite \"slackening\nin the rate of business decline in Jan\nuary.\u201d\nExchange Trading Declines.\nTrading on the Washington Stock\nExchange in January decreased sharp\nly from the preceding month, the\nSecurities and Exchange Commission\nannounces. In January of this year\nthe dollar value of sales on the local\nexchange amounted to $90,520, com\npared with $110,000 in December. The\nnumber af shares changing ownership\nalso decreased, with 1,499 in January\ncomparing with 1,626 shares in De\ncember. The commissifin announced\nthat the value of trading on all regis\ntered exchanges in the United States\nIn January, was 21 per cent lower\nthan in December.\nTrading on the Washington Ex\nchange during the past week was\nquite active, although very quiet yes\nterday. The day\u2019s only sale was in\nCity Suburban 5s, a $1,000 bond\nBelling at 60, off 2 points from the last\nprevious sale, but 5 points above the\nyear\u2019s low mark.\nNoted in Financial District.\nThe annual savings conference,\nconducted by the American Bankers\u2019\nAssociation, will be held this year on\nMarch 3 and 4 at the Hotel Robsevelt,\nNew York. Several Capital bankers\nwill attend.\nGeneral Credit, Inc., of Washington\nhas declared the regular quarterly\ndividend of $1.50 per share on the\npreferred stock and 25 cents a share\non the common, bringing payments\nfor the year ending February 28 to\n$6 on the preferred and $1.25 on the\ncommon. Both dividends are payable\nMarch 1 to stock of, record Febru\nary 25.\nA large delegation of Capital bank\ners attended the annual dinner of\nNew York Chapter, American Insti\ntute of Banking, last night, among\nthem William H. Laughlin, president\nof Washington Chapter.\nSales of American Stores in Janu\nary totaled $8,387,595, a decrease of\n$1,052,424, or 11 per cent. The pe\nriod covered this year had four Satur\ndays, against five a year ago. Sales\nfor December were 5.8 per cent above\nDecwiber. 1936.\nDeclaration of regular dividends\non three classes of stock of the\nNational Dairy Products Corp. was\npleasing to the many stockholders in\nthe Capital, where the company has\ntwo subsidiary units.\nThe regular quarterly dividend of\n$1.62% per share on Peoples Drug\nStores preferred will be paid Tuesday.\nThere has been drawn by lot for\nredemption at 102 Vi on April 1, next,\n$50,000 Pillsbury Flour Mills Co. first\n6 per cent bonds.\nINVESTMENT COMPANY\nSTOCK INDEX CLIMBS\nIpecia. Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 26 \u2014Investment\ntompanies common stock prices rose\nlast week, according to the averages\ncompiled by Distributors Group, Inc.\nThe average for the common stocks\nfor 10 leading management companies\ninfluenced by the leverage factor stood\nt 11.11 at the close of February 25,\ncompared with 10.38 on February 18.\nThe average of five mutual type\nInvestment funds closed at 11.09 on\nFebruary 25, compared with 10.68 on\nFebruary 18.\n\nt 4\nMarket Traders Are Cheered\nBy Hopes of Spring Upturn\nCommon Stocks and Junior Bonds Score\nSurprising Recoveries\u2014Rising Spring\nActivity Is Aivaited.\nBy CHARLES F. SPEARE.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 26.\u2014Due to a rising price average for securities, there is a\nhappier ending for February than for any other month since last July. 80\nWall Street is in a more cheerful mood. It has this week witnessed a sur\nprising recovery in common stocks and in listed and unlisted bonds of the\njunior variety. This was, in part, predicted on technical market conditions,\n'such as completed liquidation and a low price level, though chiefly on the\nrebound in foreign markets resulting<\u2014-\u2022-\u2014\nfrom the new diplomacy Great Britain\nhas adopted in dealing with dictator\ncountries.\nThen, too, the \u201csap is beginning to\nrise.\" However gloomy the business\noutlook may be, as the spring season\napproaches, the perennial optimists\nalways expect a quietening of the\ntempo of industry and the revival of\nEXPORTS CLIMB\n$118,674,000 Excess Seen,\nContrasts With Reverse\nSituation in 1937.\nBr the Associated Press.\nThe United States exported $118.\n674,000 more merchandise in January.\n1938, than it imported.\nExports in January. 1938. totaled\n$289,437,000, compared with $222,665,\n000 in January. 1937.\nJanuary imports totaled $170,763,\n000, compared with $240,452,000 in\nthat month a year ago.\nIn announcing these figures, the\nCommerce Department said that ex-\nports, including re-exports of foreign\nmerchandise, were 9 per cent under\nDecember. 1937, but 30 per cent above\nJanuary. 1937. The drop, the depart-\nment said, was due partly to seasonal\ninfluences.\nGrain Exports Rise.\nI A few products, notably corn and\nI wheat, were exported in substantially\nlarger quantities in January than in\nJ December.\nExports of other commodities, par\nticularly apples, canned fruit, fur\nskins and petroleum products also\nshowed an increase in value over De\ncember.\nOn the other hand, value of exports\nof leading commodities declined in\nJanuary from December. These in\ncluded leaf tobacco, raw cotton, wood\npulp, lumber, iron and steel products,\ncopper, electrical apparatus, metals\u2014\nworking machinery, motor trucks, pas\nsenger automobiles and aircraft.\nOther Lines Share Gain.\nExports of nearly all principal com\nmodities in January increased in\nvalue, compared with that month a\nyear ago. Total agricultural exports\nincreased to $91,946,000 from $61.441.~\n000 in January, 1937. with two-thirds\nof the increase resulting from the re\ncent expansion in grain shipments.\nExports of non-agricultural prod- j\nucts increased' to $194,191,000 in Jan-\nuary from $15?.623,0Q0 in January,\n1937.\nCotton cloth, petroleum and prod\nucts, iron and steel mill products, cop\nper, industrial machinery, farm im-,\nplements, automobiles, including parts'\nand accessories, and aircraft were\nitems showing substantial gains.\nGeneral imports which have de\nclined almost continuously in value\nsince March, 1937, contracted more\nin terms of dollars in January than in\nany month since November, 1930.\nSharp Drop Revealed.\nThe value was 18 per cent less than\nin December, 1937, and 29 per cent\nless than in January, 1937. The Jan\nuary value was smaller than in any\nmonth since November, 1935.\nSugar, regulated by quota, was the\nonly major commodity imported in\nlarger quantity in January than in\nDecember.\n\"Very substantial decreases\" in im\nports of grains, feeds, cocoa, unmanu\nfactured wool, raw silk, nickel and tin\naccounted fpr nearly three-fifths of\nthe decrease in th# value of total im\nports from a year ago.\nprojects that have lain dormant\nthrough the winter.\nThere are logical reasons for this\nconfidence, for outdoor employment is\ndue to increase on the farm, on the\nrailaoads and on public works, pur\nchases by the farming communities\n(See TRADERS CHEERED, Page E-2.)\nGROCERY CHAINS\nProfits May Be Improved\nby Better Price Ratio,\nPoor\u2019s Declares.\nSpecial Dispatch to Th\u00bb Star.\nNEW YORK. Feb. 16\u2014Grocery\nchain sales volume should be main\ntained at 1937 levels during the cur\nrent year, according to Poor's Industry\nInvestment Surveys.\n\u201cMeanwhile, net income may well\nimprove somewhat, for the industry\nwill have the benefit of a more favor\nj able wholesale-retail price relation\nship. Long-term prospects are for a\ncontinuation of the earnings stability\nwhich typifies this retail field.\n\u201cDollar sales of the grocery chain\nindustry recorded the smallest annual\ngain of the roceverv movement ISst\nyear.\u201d states the survey. \u201cThis in\ncrease amounted to but 1.5 per cent,\nalthough retail food prices were up\nsome 4 per cent for the year. This\nsituation reflected increasing unem\nployment In industrial centers and\npoor general business conditions\nthroughout the country.\n\u201cWhile sales volume may well de\ncline for some months yet. the indus\ntry's earnings should not be seriously\naffected. Profit margins are benefit\ning from a more rapid decline in\nwholesale food costs than is taking\nplace in retail prices. As a matter of\nfact, if the anticipated second-half\niihprovement In general business con\nditions is not accompanied by an\nabrupt rise In wholesale prices, grocery\nchains should report at least as good\nearnings this year as in 1937.\n\u201cBullish from the longer-term view\npoint is the fact that the industry\ntoday is in a much stronger physical\ncondition than ever before. Mean\nwhile, the process of substituting large\nefficient stores and supermarkets in\nchoice locations for smaller scattered\nunits continues. This action is re\nducing the overhead of the chains\nwithout sacrifice of sales volume.\n\u201cChain store taxes continue to be a\nburden, but it appears that such\nmeasures have reached a peak.\u201d\nBOND OFFER IS MADE\nBY GREEK GOVERNMENT\nSpecial Dispatch to Tht Star.\nNEW YORK. Peb. 26 \u2014The Greek\ngovernment is notifying holders of its\n5 per cent loan of 1914 bonds of an\noffer to pay 40 per cent of the face\namount of the coupons due during the\ncurrent fiscal year ending March 31,\n1938. the rate of such partial payment\nbeing 40 per cent of the sterling face\namount of each coupon as follows: On\na LO-9-11 coupon, LO-3-ll?s: on a\nL2-9-7 coupon, LO-19-10, and on a\nL12-7-11 coupon, L4-19-2.\nHolders of the bonds who desire\nto accept this payment are invited to\npresent the coupons due September 1,\n1937, and March 1, 1938, respectively,\nto J. P. Morgan ti Co., paying agents.\nWho will make the partial payments at\nthe dollar equivalent of the sterling\namount of the payments upon the\nbasis of their buying rate for exchange\non London at the time of presentation.\nHow Is Business?\nShowing Current Business Activity Compared With the\nSame Week a Year Ago.\nM>* ^onc_ July| auo' StAT. per Nov oic. jam FMAuTiTr^-\"\n1937 \u00bb38\n\u2666jo* \u2014f-Present\nBusiness\n*7\u00b0* jj#J \u2022\u2014---\u201417.29&\n-AYw\nlZ] gfcp Ago\n-i||\ntkSI!!fSS ACTIVITY for the country Indicated by Bank Debit* outride\n,,low \"Hk activity above the correaponding week of the\nprevloua \u00aeJiick nr*\u00bb\u00bb indicate dedtaai from **me week* twelve month* earlier.\nACTIVITY BY FEDeK, RESERVE DISTRICTS\nt-hcch Tran\u00abectloa\u00ab compelet^lth the \u00bbame weefr a year ago\nI N,?\u00bb**k I FbUodetehia 'cUvalaai Kiohmoad I Atlanta I\n-24.2% -22.8%_1 -lUk --38.6% I -13.8% I -1S.S% I\nC\\\u2018nV<? I 1 Minnoap^la K*a*aa City I Della* B.Fnaei*ee|\n1-^1 I-~ltf% -10.4% 1 -1.1% -lB-8%1\nLEADING BAROMETERS\nShewing Trend of Important Factors m _\n_ 70 UMBM\nFreest) t Treed From Year Ago\nBuainess In Dollars (Checks Cashed) Upward \u201417 2\nEmployment (Dept, of Labor). Downward o y\nWages (Dept, of Labor)... Do^Z\"d Z\nCost of Living (Ind. Conf. Board)... Downward 4- n a\nWholesale Prices (Fisher\u2019s Index)... Downward i o'$\nAgricultural Prices (Bureau of Labor) Downward _ jw\nMovement of Goods (Car Loadings). Downward ji g\nRetail Trade (Fed. Res. Board). Steady Z ,5\nBuilding Contracts (F. W. Dodge).. Downward 71\nFailures (Dun\u2019s). Upward 77 o\nBond Prices (Dow-Jones). Upward I2s\nStock Prices (Composite Dow-Jones) Upward 17 q\n_ Stock Mkt. Vol. (Shares Traded\u201d __ g;|\nAU right* mwi, CmmhriJg* Auodttu. Abate*\nA\nSTOCKS RETAIN\nMOST OFADVANCE\nAT WEEK\u2019S CLOSE\nFinal Prices Generally Off\nSlightly From Those of\nFriday Session.\nI. T. T. UP BRISKLY\nAS EARNINGS IMPROVE\nHopes That European Develop\nments May Bring Spanish Peace\nAlso Spur Buying.\nWHAT STOCKS DID.\nSaturday. Friday.\nAdvance* _ __ _ 148 4:t<i\nDeclines _ 254 17#\nUnchanged __ 157 158\nTotal ltsueg 55# 767\nBy FREDERICK GARDNER,\nAs*ociated Pres* Financial Writer.\nNEW YORK. Feb. 26 \u2014Stocks found\nthe going a bit rough in today s brief\nsession, but leaders finished with\nsizable net gains for the week.\nTypical Saturday, sluggishness grip\nped the list from the start, and\nclosing prices for the two-hour pro\nceedings mostly were a shade under\nthose of Friday.\nNews apparently was uninspiring\nmarketwise, and most commission\nhouse customers displayed a fondness\nfor neutral territory in view of pos\nsible happenings at home and abroad\nover the week end. Lightness of vol\nume, however, was encouraging to\nrecovery proponents who noted that\nin recent sessions the principal ac\ntivity has been on the upside.\nThe Associated Press average of 60\nissues was off .2 of a point at 46.1,\nbut, for the week, registered a net\ngain of 1.5 points. It was the fourth\nj consecutive week's advance. Today's\ntransfers totaled 303,230 shares.\nagainst 295.950 a week ago. It was\nthe best week's volume, though, since\nearly January.\nI. T. Si T. Up Briskly.\nInternational Telephone was by far\nthe liveliest performer of the day.\ngetting up 'i point at 8\u2019-. in further\nresponse to cheerier earnings pros\npects and the belief the new European\nline-up may result in settlement of\nthe war in Spain, where the company\nhas important interests.\nArmour of Illinois dropped to a new\nlow for the, year on the passing of\ndividends on both the common and\npreferred. The junior issue lost 5\u00ab\nat 5U, and the preferred was down 14\npoints at 45, also a new bottom.\nGoodrich tipped down l'\u00bb at 17\u2019i\nfollowing publication of an earnings\nstatement revealing a sizable 1937\nloss, compared with a profit of better\nthan $7,000,000 the year before.\nSteels were listless, but slightly Im\nproved as little change was predicted\nin next weeks mill operations. Rails\nwere inclined to mark time pending\nthe freight rate decision.\nMotor Leaders Down.\nDown fractions to a point or so were\nGeneral Motors at 35V Chrysler 55 V\nAmerican Telephone 139, Westing\nhouse 98't, Santa Fe 38 -V Anaconda,\n33V Montgomery Ward 36V J. I.\nCase 93, Du Pont 118 V United States\nRubber 34'* and Douglas Air\nI craft 41V\nI The main sustaining force for the\nmarket in the week was the lessening\nof tension in European affairs aided\nby the British peace gesture to Italy.\nStocks had their best day on Wednes\nday following advices from London\nconcerning the turn toward con\nciliation.\nIn addition to the fading of imme\ndiate war fears. Investment buying was\nunderstood to have appeared in se\nlected stocks on the theory the busi\nness recession had about reached the\nworst and was due for at least a mod\nerate reversal soon. \u201cInflation\u201d psy\nchology was also in evidence, but to an\nindeterminable extent.\nStimulation was found in the ability\nof the markets to override a batch of\n\u201cbad news.\u201d The list even managed\nto edge higher on Friday despite some\ndisappointment over omission of the\nChrysler dividend and anouncement\nof a cut in General Motors \u201cwhite col\nlar\u201d salaries affecting some 40,000 em\nployes.\n\nDOOLEY TO HEAD\nESSAY COMMITTEE\nAssistant Trust Officer of Hamil\nton National Named to Contest\nPost by D. C. Bankers.\nAubrey O. Dooley, assistant trust\nofficer of the Hamilton National Bank,\nhas been appointed chairman of the\n1938 Essay Contest Committee of the\nDistrict Bankers\u2019 Association, Presi\ndent Thomas J. Groom announced yes\nt e r a a y. 1 n e\nother committee\nmembers include\nH. H. McKee,\npres ldent, Na\nt i o n a 1 Capital\nBank; C. H. Pope,\nvice p r e s i dent\nand t r e a s urer,\nM u n s e y Trust\nCo.; I. J. Roberts,\nassistant cashier,\nRiggs National,\nand James A.\nSoper, vice presi\ndent and cashier,\nLincoln National.\nUnder new rules\nAubrey O. Deeley.\nxor mas mere will be two classes\nof contestants\u2014one for bank employes\nand one for junior officers. The con\ntest is open to all members of Wash\nington Chapter, American Institute\nof Banking, in good standing on April\n1 who are employes of banks which\nare members of the District Bankers\u2019\nAssociation\u2014except senior executive\nofficers and individuals who may have\nwon two previous contests.\nFirst and second prizes are to be\nawarded in each class. First prize\nwill be a trip to the District Bankers\u2019\nAssociation Convention, to be held\nJune 9-12 at Hot Springs, Va. Second\nprize in each class will be 150, paid\nby the contestant\u2019s<bank, as will be the\nconvention expenses of the first-place\nwinner*.\nh\nDow Jones Stock Averages\n(Re\u00ablstered United States Patent Office.)\nThe high, low and closing averages of 30 industrial stocks as compiled by Dow Jones Co. are\nsho7vn above. Extending back for four months, the top of each vertical line represents the\nhigh 7ohile the bottom represents the low point of each day. The small intersecting horizontal\nline represents the closing average. The high and low averages of each month are given on\neither side of the average lines. Industrials advanced but failed to hold all of their gains recorded\non Wednesday and Friday.\n\u00bb-'-1-r-j-1-1-,-,\u2014\n40-1 RAILROADS]---43\n34.26\nNOV 13\nr*'L 35\n\u2022V V r^if,*r tf*Vi,\n30 V I^tn*4-\u2022\u2019V\u2014I-\u00bb\no\u201d\u20191, \u2018lf\u00bb \u2019V/\nI 2T.ng\n--1-1-1-1--1-1--I --1_l-L- i i I FEB 3 I\nThe Dow Jones averages of 20 railroad stocks are compiled above in the same manner.\nRails forged ahead but also lost part of their gains at the week\u2019s close.\n1 i 1 i i r\u2014\u2014i i r-i-r\u2014i-i-1-1-1\nutilities]\n23.48\n25\u2014NOV. 10-aS-------125\n\u25baU NOV 27 2186\nT**. JAN 12\n\u2018-V Wn-f\n&-15? V*-\"\nDEC 2*\n118.25\nFEB 3\n-1-1-1_\u00bb-l l ill\nAverages of 20 utilities are shown in the third, section of the compilation. This group\nmade slow headway but were around their best levels on Saturday.\nThe volume of shares traded on the stock market for the same period is shown above.\nLt\nTotal for Fourth Quarter\nShows Increase Over\nPrevious Period.\nBy the Associsted Press.\nNEW YORK. Feb. 26.\u2014L. C. Smith\nCorona Typewriters, Inc., and sub\nsidiaries reported for the quarter end\ning December 31, 1937. net income of\n$200,613 after depreciation, depletion,\namoritization. interest. Federal and\nCanadian income taxes and surtax on\nundistributed profits.\nThis is equivalent to 65 cents per\ncommon share after preferred divi\ndends. and compares with 43 cents per\nshare earnings for the previous quarter,\nand $1.36 per share for the quarter\nending December 31, 1936.\nAmerican Safety Razor.\nAmerican Safety Razor Corp. re\nported consolidated net income for\n1937 of $1,294,243 after depreciation\nand Federal taxes, equal to $2.47 a\ncapital share, compared to net income\nof $1,414,226, or $2.70 a share for the\nprevious year. Directors voted the\nregular quarterly dividend of 50 cents,\npayable March 30 to stock of record\nMarch 10.\nFrisco Railway.\nThe St. Louis-San Francisco Rail\nway Co. reported a deficit of $319,916\nin its net railway operating income\nduring January, a decrease of $522,646\nfrom the same month a year ago.\nTotal operating revenues for the month\nwere $3,541,814, a decrease of $690,449\nfrom January, 1937. Total operating\nexpenses were $3,448,055, a decrease of\n$142,281.\nMissouri Pacific.\nST. LOUIS. Feb. 26 (\u00a3>).\u2014'The Mis\nsouri Pacific Railroad reported today\noperating revenues of January, 1938,\ndecreased 13.6 per cent, as compared\nwith the same month in 1937, dropping\nto $6,527,091.\nThe January. 1937, figure was $7,\n554,597. The decrease was 35.6 per\ncent under January, 1930, when op\nerating revenue was $10,131,231, the\nroad reported.\nThe road reported a net operating\ndeficit for January, 1938, of $65,944,\ncompared with a deficit of $17,301 for\nJanuary. 1937, and a net operating\nincome of $5,423 in January, 1930.\nOther Carriers Report.\nNet operating income, before fixed\ncharges and other income, of other\nrailroads reporting for January in\ncluded\nAla. Great Southern _ 5H?8N5\nBaltimore Sc Ohio-206.001 2.021 04o\nBoston Ac Maine_534,304 7l'0>>8\nBurlington 32.011 539!770\nChicago N\u2019western.-- 770,705 341.680\nGulf Coast 354.850 454.678\nSouthern Railway 278,423 1.340.066\nDela.. Lark. A West n 06.105 438 318\nSeaboard Air Line _ 101511 566.682\nSt L.. Southwestern. 33.128 146,860\nVirginian _ 661,054 501.166'\nk\nThree lines in each of the three market divisions show the\nhigh, low and closing Dow Jones averages for the past week.\nWeekly Financial High Lights\nBy4he Associated Press. This week. Prev. week. Year ago.\nBrokers' loans.. *578,000 *588,000 *1,053,000\nHoldings U. S. securities. 2,584,015 2,564,015 2,430,227\nGold reserve. 9,167,600 9,163,600 8,847,384\nRediscounts. 10,148 9,920 4,107\nBank clearings. 3,804,457 4,297,187 5,591,156\nElectric output (kilowatt hours)\nweek ended February 19. 2,059,165 2,052,302 3,211,818\n(Final three ciphers omitted in above.)\nCar loadings, week ended Feb. 19... 535,790 542,991 711,314\nCrude oil produced (barrels)_ 3,369,250 3,324,500 3,295,950\nStock sales, N. Y. Stock Exchange_ 3,978,393 3,3*17,940 9,959,230\nBond sales, N. Y. Stock Exchange_ *29.444,835 *33,609,400 *58,266,000\nNew financing. 8,741,000 1,301,000 18,547,000\nFederal Reserve ratio- 80.4% 80.3% 80.4%\nSteel output rate_ 30.4% 31.0% 82.5%\nCall money rate- 1% 1% 1%\nTime money rate___..... 114 -1 Vs 1!-4-1'.i% 1V4%\nCommercial paper--........ 1% 1%\n1 1\nSteel and Motor Outputs\nDown Slightly With Freight\nLoadings.\nWEATHER IS ADVERSE\nFACTOR IN SOME AREAS\nMost Cities Report Recessions\nFrom Previous Week as Well\nas From 1937 Levels.\nBy THOMAS E. FLANAGAN,\nAssociated Press Financial Writer.\nThe Nation's business barometer fell\na little during the past week.\nIn three major divisions\u2014steel op\nerations, carloadings and motor pro\nduction\u2014there were small declines.\nThe electric power industry made a\nslight gain, but experts said it was less\nthan normal.\nRetail trade failed to live up to the\npromise of reports made a week ago.\nwhen some leading cities showed\ngains.\nAlthough the Commerce Depart\nment noted weather as an extenuating\nfactor in some sections, it said retail\nturnover had \"slipped back into low\ngear.\"\nin its report on business in 37 cities,\nthe department said:\n\u201cWith only a few isolated excep\ntions. every city showed losses in\ntrade, compared with the like period\nlast year. Most of these likewise re\nvealed a let-down from the previous\nweek.\nNew urieans Gains.\n\"The only city in the country where\nretail business was good, from a com\nparative standpoint, was New Orleans,\nwhere precamival sales put the vol\nume 25 per cent ahead of last year.\u201d\nThe Associated Press index of in\ndustrial activity fell to 69.3. the lowest\nsince December, 1934. The week pre\nvious it was 70, a year ago 103.1.\nSteel operations receded to 30.4 per\ncent of capacity from 31 the week\nbefore, the American Iron Steel In\nstitute estimated. A month ago the\nrate was 32.7, a year ago 82 5.\nSteel men said the recent removal\nof price uncertainties had cleared the\nair. A few companies did the best\nbusiness in several weeks, it was\nreported.\nRailroads Watched.\nSteel experts focused attention on\nthe railroad industry, which has gone\nbefore the Interstate Commerce Com\nmission with a plea for a 15 per cent\nfreight rate increase. Some said sev\neral roads had been inquiring for\nsteel in anticipation of a decision\nshortly by the commission.\nIron Age said:\n\u201cIn industry generally steel is being\nconsumed at a rate faster than it is\nbeing produced. One large steel com\npany. for example, in a survey among\nits larger customers, found that some\nwere operating up to 60 per cent, or\ndouble the steel rate.\u201d\nAlthough the approach of spring\nusually brings an upturn in building\nactivity, thus far no speeding up in\nstructural steel buying has been noted.\nAuto Production Sags.\nThe automobile industry, a main\nstay of the steel makers, slowed down\nproduction to 56,677 units, compared\nwith 59.100 the previous week and\n115.360 in the like 1937 week. Ward s\nAutomotive Reports said, however, that\noutput \u201cis on the verge of a normal\nseasonal advance.\u201d\nOne footnote on the automobile\nindustry came from General Motors\nCorp., which announced pay cuts for\nsalaried workers. Chairman Alfred\nP. Sloan. jr\u201e said the action was\ntaken because of the \u201cdrastic reduc\ntion\u201d in the corporation's business.\nAnother straw in the wind was the\ndecision of directors of Chrysler Corp.\nnot to declare a dividend. The pre\nvious dividend, $3, was paid on De\ncember 13. B. E. Hutchinson, chair\nman of the Finance Committee, said\nthe board had based its decision on\nthe \u201cobscure\u201d near-term business out\nlook.\nFreight Loadings Off.\nIn the week ended February 19\ncarloadings totaled 535.970, a decline\nof 1.3 per cent from the preceding\nweek and 24.7 per cent under the like\n1937 period, the Association of Amer\nican Railroads reported.\nThe figures came in the wake of\nreports which showed a sharp drop\nfrom 1937 in January net operating\nincome of several railroads.\nFor the first time this year electric\npower output gained over the previous\nweek. The total of 2,059.165.000 kilo\nwatt hours in the week ended Feb\nruary 19, reported by the Edison Elec\ntric Institute, was 0.3 of 1 per cent\nabove the preceding week, but 6.9 per\ncent under the like 1937 week.\nConstruction Down.\nWhile business moved toward spring\ninfluences, statistics on engineering\nconstruction awards assumed signifi\ncance. In the week ended Tuesday\nthe total was down to $40,161,000 from\n$45,001,000 the previous week and\ncompared with $72,178,000 in the cor\nresponding 1937 week. Engineering\nNews-Record said. It was noted pub\nlic pfojects had gained over the pre\nvious week and private work dropped.\nBank clearings were down 32 per\ncent from 1937 in 22 leading cities in\nthe week ended February 23, Dun\nBradstreet said.\nThe Federal Reserve Board reported\nthat bank loans to business declined\nIn the week ended February 16, re\nsuming a downtrend interrupted by\nthe limited advance in the previous\nweek.\nPOOR CO. REPORTS\nHIGHER NET FOR 1937\nSpeWal Dispatch to Th\u00ab Star\nNEW YORK. Feb. 26.\u2014Poor Co.,\nChicago, manufacturers of railroad\nequipment, reported net income in\n1937 totaled $827,286 after charges\nand Federal surtax, equal to $1.61 a\nshare of class \"B\u201d stock. This com\npared with $418,497, or 49 cents on\nclass \"B\" in 1936.\nA","height":"31112","width":"22452"}}
